Under the electron microscope, HEV particles in infected DRG neurons were identified as spherical particles inside vesicles or as electron-dense materials in the process of budding into the intracellular membranous cisternae (Fig. 2, Fig. 3
), as described previously (Clarke and McFerran, 1971, Mengeling et al., 1972, Yagami et al., 1986). Progeny virions had an electron-lucent or dense center, and ranged in diameter from 65 to 116 nm (73.4 ± 12.1 nm, mean ± SEM, n
 = 55). The outer surfaces of the viral envelopes were sometimes covered by a layer of well-defined projections, forming a typical “corona” profile (see the inset in Fig. 3D). As control, no similar structures were found in the samples from vehicle-inoculated animals (Fig. 4
).
